<paragraph id="574036D4FFF94174CA81EC35FDDC2516" blockId="15.[151,1437,1260,1792]" box="[199,622,1369,1395]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF94174CA81EC35FEE12516" bold="true" box="[199,339,1369,1395]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFF94174CB1CEC35FE6D2516" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[346,479,1369,1395]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn 1991</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFF94174CBADEC35FDDC2516" author="Hemp, C." box="[491,622,1369,1395]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" refId="ref16956" refString="Hemp, C. (2021) A Field Guide to the Bushcrickets, Wetas and Raspy Crickets of Tanzania and Kenya. Senckenberg Gesellschaft fur Naturforschung, Frankfurt, 451 pp." type="book" year="2021">Hemp 2021</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF94174CA81EC11FEA7264D" blockId="15.[151,1437,1260,1792]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF94174CA81EC11FED025F2" bold="true" box="[199,354,1405,1431]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174CBA6EC11FD9525F2" box="[480,551,1405,1431]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFF94174C940EC11FCEF25F2" box="[774,861,1405,1431]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and spectrum of the song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174CEF5EC11FB4825FD" box="[1203,1274,1405,1432]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1287,1311]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,201,1247]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Power spectra of male calling songs in Hetrodini species" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392725/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFF94174C846ECCDFDDC25DE" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[512,622,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174C9E0ECCDFC4D25DE" box="[934,1023,1441,1467]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1216,1240]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,204,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,1192]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Cosmoderus and Enyaliopsis (figures of E. iaculator based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Cosmoderus femoratus, B Enyaliopsis bloyeti. C Enyaliopsis carolinus, D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, song type A, E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 (near ephippiatus), song type B, F Enyaliopsis iaculator, G Enyaliopsis jennae, H Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-ms-section)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392733/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
) consists of long series of syllables (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFF94174CA98ECA9FEBD25BA" box="[222,271,1477,1503]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">type</typeStatus>
B in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174CB0AECA9FE222585" box="[332,400,1477,1504]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) with varying duration (1–40 s measured). Surprisingly also in SRR relatively large differences were found (12–42 Hz), which may be at least partly explained by temperature differences during recording (18–26ºC).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF94174CA81EF5DFE04260A" blockId="15.[151,1437,1260,1792]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF94174CA81EF5DFE8D262E" bold="true" box="[199,319,1585,1611]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Genitalia.</emphasis>
The central part of the genitalic sclerites (titillator) of our specimen (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174CE34EF5DFB7E262E" box="[1138,1228,1585,1611]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-41@13.[151,1436,237,1179]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Titillator and genitalic sclerites in Hetrodini, Enyaliopsina. First row A Cosmoderus femoralis (CH8627), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti (Kazimzumbwi), C Enyaliopsis carolinus (Minziro), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus (Rau Forest); second row E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 near ephippiatus (Mwala), F Enyaliopsis jennae (Uluguru), G Enyaliopsis spec. 2 (Mpwapwa), H Enyaliopsis spec. 3 (East Chenene); third row I Gymnoproctus rammei (Puge Simbo), J Gymnoproctus spec. (East Chenene)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392735/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
) is similar to that figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFF94174CB53EF39FE00260A" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[277,434,1621,1647]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn (1991)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF94174CA81EF15FE2F269A" blockId="15.[151,1437,1260,1792]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF94174CA81EF15FEC926F6" bold="true" box="[199,379,1657,1683]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Chromosomes:</emphasis>
2n = 26 (24 + neo-XY), FN = 29; pairs 1 and 2 meta/submetacentric, 3–12 acrocentric, neo-X acrocentric and neo-Y meta/submetacentric (
<specimenCount id="41F9FD5DFFF94174C8DCEFF1FD5926DD" box="[666,747,1693,1720]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" type="male">1 male</specimenCount>
); thin C-bands in the paracentromeric region in all chromosomes including the sex chromosomes, and thick telomeric C-positive blocks in three acrocentric medium-sized pairs 3, 4, 5 (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174CB6CEF89FE23269A" box="[298,401,1765,1791]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1628,1652]" captionTargetBox="[203,1395,181,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-23@18.[172,1415,181,1604]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Examples of chromosome number and heterochromatin C-banding of mitotic male (A–C, G–K) and mitotic female complements (D), as well as diplotene/diakinesis (C, E, I on the right), and metaphase I (F) for the following Hetrodini taxa: A Cosmoderus femoralis, 2n = 24 + X0 (CH8626), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti, 2n = 28 + X0 (HE114), C Enyaliopsis carolinus, 2n =24 + neo-XY (CH8625), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, 2n = 26 + XX (female CH7849), E Enyaliopsis jennae, 2n = 26 + neo- XY (HE87), F Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa, 2n = 26 + X0 (CH8353), G Gymnoproctus rammei, 2n = 26 + X0 (CH8763), H Gymnoproctus spec., 2n = 26 + X0 (CH7953), I Spalacomimus magnus, 2n = 16 + X0 (CH7945), J Spalacomimus verruciferus, 2n = 22 + neo-XY (CH7897), K Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, 2n = 22 + neo-XY (CH7899). Bi-armed chromosomes (meta/submeta/subacrocentric) are marked with numbers (A, C, D, F–I); in the neo-XY system, sex chromosomes form association in diplotene (C) and metaphase I (I); arrowheads indicate interstitial C-bands in 1 (A, E, J, K) and 2 (I) pairs; asterisks (*) marked distal C-bands in 3, 4, 5 (C), 3, 4 (D), 2-heteromorphic (G, H) pair; X = neo-X and Y = neo-Y sex chromosomes. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392745" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392745/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
